    <div id="block-miller-page-title" class="miller-title-wrapper">
  
    
      
  <h1><span>July 12, 1966: Speech on U.S. Foreign Policy in Asia</span>
</h1>


    <div class="share-trigger-mobile"></div>
</div>
<div id="block-mainpagecontent">
  
    
      <article role="article" class="presidential-speech">

  
    

  <div class="ps-container video-container">
    <div class="presidential-speeches--sidebar">
      
<div  class="about-this-episode">
    <h3>About this speech</h3>
      
<div  class="about-this-episode--inner">
      
            <p class="president-name">Lyndon B. Johnson</p>
      
            <p class="episode-date">July 12, 1966</p>
      
  <div class="speech-location-container">
    <span class="speech-label">Location</span>
              <span class="speech-loc">National Archives</span>
          </div>

            <div class="about-sidebar--intro"><p>President Johnson’s speech is directed at explaining the U.S. interest in Asia and how he plans to achieve peace.&nbsp; He explains that Asia is critical to the success of U.S. achievements around the world, and that the goal of the involvement is to generate an acceptable peace between communist and non-communist neighbors in Southeast Asia.&nbsp; Johnson lists the achievements that must be made to gain peace, and defends his position against those who suspect imperialist motives.&nbsp; He refuses to retreat from U.S. obligations in Vietnam and believes American influence can bring about a peaceful “Pacific Era.”</p>
</div>
      
  </div>
  </div>
    </div>

    <div class="presidential-speeches--body-wrapper">
     <a href="/the-presidency/presidential-speeches" class="back-to-listing--cta">Presidential Speeches</a> <span class="nav-separator">|</span> <label class="presidential-speeches--label">Lyndon B. Johnson Presidency</label>
      <h2 class="presidential-speeches--title"><span>July 12, 1966: Speech on U.S. Foreign Policy in Asia</span>
</h2>
      
<div  class="presidential-speeches--body">
      <div class="video-parent">
